HEXSTRIKE ADDED FEATURES
========================

================================================================================
PRE-CTF SETUP MAP  (run every step IN ORDER before starting a challenge)
================================================================================

This is the exact sequence of manual calls required so that every log entry in
tool_logger.log carries correct metadata from the first tool use onward.

  STEP 1 — Start the server (terminal, once per machine session)
    python3 hexstrike_server.py

  STEP 2 — Set LLM identity  [MANUAL — required once, or when model/client changes]
    set_llm_identity(
        model  = "<model-id>",    # e.g. "claude-sonnet-4-6", "deepseek-r1", "gpt-4o"
        client = "<client-name>"  # e.g. "claude-code", "cursor", "5ire", "roo-code"
    )
    *** Without this call, every log entry shows model=unknown / client=unknown ***

  STEP 3 — Set CTF metadata  [MANUAL — required before each new challenge]
    set_ctf_metadata(
        ctf_difficulty = "<level>",     # Easy | Medium | Hard | Insane
        ctf_type       = "<category>",  # Web | Pwn | Crypto | Forensics | Reversing |
                                        # OSINT | Misc | Network | Cloud | Mobile
        prompt_type    = "<strategy>"   # direct | chain-of-thought | few-shot |
                                        # zero-shot | role-play | agentic
    )
    *** Without this call, CTF fields in every log entry show "unknown" ***

  STEP 4 — Start the timer  [MANUAL — call at the exact moment you begin the challenge]
    start_timer()
    *** No parameters needed. Must be called BEFORE issuing any tool commands. ***
    *** Without this, elapsed_seconds in log entries will be null.             ***

  --- now work on the challenge; all tool calls log automatically ---

  STEP 5 — Mark success  [MANUAL — call as soon as the outcome is known]
    set_success("<outcome>")
    # "true" / "yes" / "success"  →  solved
    # "false" / "no" / "fail"     →  not solved
    # "partial"                   →  partial flag / incomplete
    # "in-progress"               →  still working (update again when done)
    *** Without this call, success=unknown in all log entries after this point ***

  STEP 6 — Stop the timer  [MANUAL — call immediately after set_success()]
    stop_timer()
    *** No parameters needed. Records elapsed wall-clock seconds. ***

  STEP 7 — Verify (optional but recommended)
    get_ctf_session_info()
    *** Returns the full config snapshot: model, client, difficulty, type,
        prompt_type, success, timer_start, timer_end, elapsed_seconds.      ***
    *** Use this to confirm everything is set correctly before reviewing logs ***

  Quick copy-paste template (fill in the <…> placeholders):
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    set_llm_identity(model="<model>", client="<client>")
    set_ctf_metadata(ctf_difficulty="<Easy|Medium|Hard|Insane>",
                     ctf_type="<Web|Pwn|Crypto|…>",
                     prompt_type="<direct|agentic|…>")
    start_timer()
    # … solve the challenge …
    set_success("<true|partial|fail>")
    stop_timer()
    get_ctf_session_info()   # optional verify
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

================================================================================


1. TOOL DECISION LOGGER
   Logs every tool chosen by the decision engine to tool_logger.log.
   Each entry includes the tool name, its position in the LLM chain, effectiveness
   score, attack chain priority, target, target type, and objective.

   Files:
   - hexstrike_server.py : tool_logger file handler setup (module level, on import)
   - hexstrike_server.py : _get_attack_chain_priority() looks up tool priority in attack pattern chains
   - hexstrike_server.py : log_tool_decision() writes one log entry per tool per scan
   - hexstrike_server.py : select_optimal_tools() calls log_tool_decision() on every scan
   - tool_logger.log     : output log file


2. LLM AND CLIENT IDENTITY
   Lets the user set which LLM model and client are being used with HexStrike.
   Saved to hexstrike_config.json and automatically included in every log entry.
   Call once to set it, call again anytime to update it.

   *** REQUIRES MANUAL INPUT — must be called before any CTF work ***

   MCP tool: set_llm_identity(model, client)
     model   [REQUIRED] — the LLM model identifier string.
               Examples: "claude-sonnet-4-6", "claude-opus-4-6", "deepseek-r1",
                         "deepseek-v3", "gpt-4o", "gemini-2.0-flash"
               Use the exact model ID string for accurate research data.
     client  [REQUIRED] — the AI client / interface being used.
               Examples: "claude-code", "claude-desktop", "cursor", "roo-code",
                         "5ire", "trae", "vscode-copilot"

   MCP tool: get_llm_identity()
     No parameters. Returns the currently saved model and client strings.

   Files:
   - hexstrike_server.py : _load_hexstrike_config() reads config from disk
   - hexstrike_server.py : _save_hexstrike_config() writes config to disk
   - hexstrike_server.py : get_llm_identity() returns current model and client
   - hexstrike_server.py : POST /api/config/set-identity HTTP endpoint to set identity
   - hexstrike_server.py : GET  /api/config/get-identity HTTP endpoint to read identity
   - hexstrike_mcp.py    : set_llm_identity() MCP tool to set model and client
   - hexstrike_mcp.py    : get_llm_identity() MCP tool to read current identity
   - hexstrike_config.json : persisted identity config file


3. UNIVERSAL TOOL CALL LOGGER (ALL LLMs)
   *** NO MANUAL INPUT REQUIRED — logging is fully automatic ***
   Every tool call whether made by Claude, DeepSeek, or any other LLM is now
   logged to tool_logger.log. Logging happens at three levels:

   a) MCP level: catches all hexstrike MCP tool calls from any LLM client
      (Claude Code, DeepSeek via 5ire/cursor/roo-code, GPT-4, etc.)
   b) Hook level: catches Claude native tools (Bash, Read, Grep, WebSearch, etc.)
      via a Claude Code PreToolUse hook. Only fires when Claude Code is the client.
   c) LLM Proxy (hooks/llm_proxy.py): catches native LLM tool calls (DeepSeek
      code_interpreter, roo-code file tools, etc.) from ANY client by sitting
      between the client and the real LLM API. See section 7 for setup.

   Hexstrike tools are logged only at the MCP level. Native LLM tools are logged
   by the hook (Claude Code) or the proxy (all other clients). No duplicates.

   Log entry format (session-structured):
     ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     SESSION START
       Model     : <llm-model>
       Client    : <client>
       CTF Type  : <type>
       Difficulty: <difficulty>
       Prompt    : <prompt_type>
     ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     TOOL_CALL | [hexstrike] <tool_name> | <params>
     TOOL_CALL | [claude] <tool_name> | <params>
     ...
     ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     SESSION END
       Model     : <llm-model>    Client    : <client>
       CTF Type  : <type>         Difficulty: <difficulty>
       Prompt    : <prompt_type>  Elapsed   : <seconds>s
       Success   : <outcome>
     ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

   Session markers are written by hexstrike_mcp.py when start_timer/stop_timer fire.
   Native LLM tool calls (Claude Bash/Read/Write etc.) are logged by the hook only
   within an active session. No tool calls are logged before start_timer or after
   stop_timer — eliminating setup-phase noise.

   Files:
   - hexstrike_mcp.py        : _MCP_TOOL_LOG_PATH path to shared log file
   - hexstrike_mcp.py        : _log_mcp_tool_call() logs each MCP tool call
   - hexstrike_mcp.py        : _load_mcp_config() reads config for metadata
   - hexstrike_server.py     : POST /api/log/tool-call HTTP fallback log endpoint
   - hooks/tool_logger_hook.py : PreToolUse hook script for Claude and DeepSeek native tools
   - ~/.claude/settings.json : hook registration (PreToolUse points to hook script)
   - tool_logger.log         : unified output log file

   How to use:
   - Nothing extra needed. Every tool call is logged automatically.
   - To identify which LLM is running, call set_llm_identity() first (see feature 2).
   - DeepSeek users: set model to "deepseek-r1" or "deepseek-v3" via set_llm_identity().


4. CTF SESSION METADATA
   *** REQUIRES MANUAL INPUT — call before starting each new challenge ***
   Lets you attach CTF challenge info to every log entry. You can set the difficulty,
   the category, and the type of prompting strategy being used. All of it gets saved
   to hexstrike_config.json and included automatically in all tool_logger.log entries
   from that point forward.

   MCP tool: set_ctf_metadata(ctf_difficulty, ctf_type, prompt_type)
     All three parameters are optional strings — supply only what you want to update.
     Omitting a parameter leaves its existing value unchanged in the config.

     ctf_difficulty [optional] — difficulty rating of the challenge.
                     Accepted: "Easy", "Medium", "Hard", "Insane"
                     Custom values are also accepted (any non-empty string).

     ctf_type       [optional] — challenge category / domain.
                     Accepted: "Web", "Pwn", "Crypto", "Forensics", "Reversing",
                               "OSINT", "Misc", "Network", "Cloud", "Mobile"
                     Custom values are also accepted.

     prompt_type    [optional] — prompting strategy used with the LLM.
                     Accepted: "direct", "chain-of-thought", "few-shot",
                               "zero-shot", "role-play", "agentic"
                     Custom values are also accepted.

     At least one parameter must be provided or the call returns an error.

   MCP tool: get_ctf_session_info()
     No parameters. Returns all current CTF session fields plus timer data.

   Fields stored in config:
   - ctf_difficulty : Easy, Medium, Hard, Insane (or any custom value)
   - ctf_type       : Web, Pwn, Crypto, Forensics, Reversing, OSINT, Misc,
                      Network, Cloud, Mobile (or any custom value)
   - prompt_type    : direct, chain-of-thought, few-shot, zero-shot,
                      role-play, agentic (or any custom value)

   Files:
   - hexstrike_server.py : _load_hexstrike_config() loads all config fields
   - hexstrike_server.py : _update_hexstrike_config() partial config update helper
   - hexstrike_server.py : get_ctf_meta() returns just the CTF fields
   - hexstrike_server.py : POST /api/config/set-ctf-meta HTTP endpoint
   - hexstrike_server.py : GET  /api/config/get-ctf-meta HTTP endpoint
   - hexstrike_server.py : log_tool_decision() includes CTF fields in every TOOL_DECISION line
   - hexstrike_mcp.py    : set_ctf_metadata() MCP tool
   - hexstrike_mcp.py    : get_ctf_session_info() MCP tool
   - hexstrike_config.json : persisted config file

   How to use (MCP tool):
     set_ctf_metadata(
         ctf_difficulty="Hard",
         ctf_type="Binary",
         prompt_type="direct"
     )
     # all fields are optional, only pass what you want to update
     # call again anytime to change one or more fields mid-session

   How to use (HTTP):
     POST http://127.0.0.1:8888/api/config/set-ctf-meta
     Body: {"ctf_difficulty": "Medium", "ctf_type": "Web", "prompt_type": "direct"}

     GET  http://127.0.0.1:8888/api/config/get-ctf-meta


5. SUCCESS STATUS
   *** REQUIRES MANUAL INPUT — call when the challenge outcome is known ***
   Mark whether the CTF challenge was solved, failed, or partially done.
   Gets saved to hexstrike_config.json and included in all log entries after that.

   MCP tool: set_success(success)
     success [REQUIRED] — a single string describing the outcome.
               Accepted values:
               "true" / "yes" / "success"  →  challenge solved
               "false" / "no" / "fail"     →  challenge not solved
               "partial"                   →  partial flag or incomplete solution
               "in-progress"               →  still working (can call again later)

               Call this BEFORE stop_timer() so the final log entry
               already carries the correct success value.

   Files:
   - hexstrike_server.py : POST /api/config/set-success HTTP endpoint
   - hexstrike_mcp.py    : set_success() MCP tool
   - hexstrike_config.json : persisted config file

   How to use (HTTP):
     POST http://127.0.0.1:8888/api/config/set-success
     Body: {"success": "true"}


6. SESSION TIMER
   *** REQUIRES MANUAL INPUT — start_timer() and stop_timer() must be called by hand ***
   Start and stop a wall-clock timer for each CTF challenge. The elapsed time gets
   stored in hexstrike_config.json and added to every log entry so you can see how
   long the LLM took to use each tool.

   MCP tool: start_timer()
     No parameters. Records the current UTC timestamp as timer_start.
     Call this BEFORE issuing any scanning or exploitation tools for the challenge.
     If called again mid-challenge, it resets the timer.

   MCP tool: stop_timer()
     No parameters. Records timer_end and computes elapsed_seconds.
     Call this AFTER set_success() at the very end of the challenge.
     Returns: { timer_start, timer_end, elapsed_seconds }

   Files:
   - hexstrike_server.py   : start_timer() / POST /api/config/start-timer HTTP endpoint
   - hexstrike_server.py   : stop_timer()  / POST /api/config/stop-timer  HTTP endpoint
   - hexstrike_mcp.py      : start_timer() MCP tool
   - hexstrike_mcp.py      : stop_timer()  MCP tool
   - hexstrike_config.json : stores timer_start, timer_end, elapsed_seconds
   - tool_logger.log       : TIMER_START and TIMER_STOP marker lines written on each call

   How to use (MCP tools):
     start_timer()   # call at the beginning of a challenge
     ...             # work on the challenge
     stop_timer()    # call when finished, returns elapsed_seconds

   How to use (HTTP):
     POST http://127.0.0.1:8888/api/config/start-timer   (no body needed)
     POST http://127.0.0.1:8888/api/config/stop-timer    (no body needed)

   Typical full session workflow:
     set_llm_identity(model="deepseek-chat", client="5ire")
     set_ctf_metadata(ctf_difficulty="Hard", ctf_type="Binary", prompt_type="direct")
     start_timer()
     # solve the challenge
     # manually set success after reviewing results
     stop_timer()
     # every tool call in between gets logged with all the metadata and elapsed time



7. LLM API PROXY (roo-code, 5ire, trae, cursor — non-Claude clients)
   *** START ONCE — then configure your client to point at it ***
   Intercepts native LLM tool calls (DeepSeek code_interpreter, roo-code file
   tools, etc.) that bypass both the Claude Code hook and the MCP logger.
   Works with any OpenAI-compatible client by acting as a transparent pass-through.

   File:
   - hooks/llm_proxy.py   : proxy server

   How to start:
     python3 hooks/llm_proxy.py                              # DeepSeek, port 8889
     python3 hooks/llm_proxy.py --backend https://api.openai.com --port 8890
     python3 hooks/llm_proxy.py --backend https://api.deepseek.com --port 8889

   Client configuration (roo-code / 5ire / trae / cursor):
     Base URL : http://127.0.0.1:8889/v1
     API Key  : <your real DeepSeek/OpenAI key — passed through unchanged>

   What gets logged:
   - Every tool_call returned by the LLM in its API response
   - Both streaming (SSE) and non-streaming responses are handled
   - Source label is auto-detected from the model name:
       deepseek-r1 / deepseek-v3  → [deepseek]
       gpt-4o / o3                → [openai]
       gemini-*                   → [gemini]
       llama-* / meta-*           → [llama]
       anything else              → [<model-slug>]
   - Like the hook, only logs within an active session (after start_timer)

   What does NOT get logged:
   - Hexstrike MCP tool calls (those are caught by the MCP-level logger)
   - The proxy does NOT modify, block, or inspect request bodies
     beyond reading the model name and stream flag.
